<p>If you hold a sizable amount of Monero and <a href="https://mymonero.com">mymonero.com</a> is not an option for security reasons (which it shouldnâ€™t if you have a large stash) youâ€™ll have to get the Moneroâ€™s core client.</p>

<p>That means downloading the full blockchain and creating a seed for your XMR wallet.</p>

<p>The setup is not difficult, especially now that there is a GUI option for those who are not comfortable with command line clients. However, you should consider the size of the Monero blockchain: it is around 10 GB now so youâ€™ll use a lot of data. And even though itâ€™s not really a big issue for most people these days, the blockchain also grows so make sure you have enough space on your hard drive. <a href="https://forum.getmonero.org/20/general-discussion/315/blockchain-size-forecast">This thread</a> on Monero forums says 57 GB blockchain by 2020 is a reasonable estimate so with some commonly retailed 1 TB external HDD you should be well beyond OK even for a very long term storage.</p>

<p>If you want to store a lot of XMR you should go for the CLI wallet. A <a href="http://monero.stackexchange.com/questions/3237/is-the-gui-safe-for-storing-thousands-of-monero">Stack Overflow thread here</a> explains this code of good practice: The GUI wallet works with the same deamon as the CLI wallet, it is just a wrapper. The GUI shouldnâ€™t be less secure than the CLI - but you just donâ€™t know. The CLI client has been used since Moneroâ€™s inception, it is thoroughly tested by real users. The GUI wallet is new. Leave it some time.</p>

<h4 id="monero-cli-wallet">Monero CLI Wallet</h4>

<p>You can download Monero Core for your OS <a href="https://getmonero.org/downloads/">here</a>.</p>

<p><a target="_blank" href="https://www.altcointrading.net/img/xmr/monero-cli-1.jpg" title="AltcoinTrading.NET - How to setup Monero core wallet (for dummies)"><figure class="border"><amp-img itemprop="image" src="https://www.altcointrading.net/img/xmr/monero-cli-1.jpg" alt="How to setup Monero core wallet (for dummies)" title="AltcoinTrading.NET - How to setup Monero core wallet (for dummies)" layout="responsive" width="700px" height="360px"></amp-img></figure></a></p>

<p>If youâ€™re a real human the only two scripts youâ€™ll use are <code class="highlighter-rouge">monerod</code> and <code class="highlighter-rouge">monero-wallet-cli</code>. In a console app (like iTerm on Mac) simply navigate into the extracted file you downloaded from the link above and run <code class="highlighter-rouge">./monerod</code>.</p>

<p>MoneroD means Monero deamon, it will start downloading the blockchain. This will take a few hours. You should see random gibberish of this kind until the blockchain is fully synced:</p>

<p><a target="_blank" href="https://www.altcointrading.net/img/xmr/monero-cli-2.png" title="AltcoinTrading.NET - How to setup Monero core wallet (for dummies)"><figure class="border"><amp-img itemprop="image" src="https://www.altcointrading.net/img/xmr/monero-cli-2.png" alt="How to setup Monero core wallet (for dummies)" title="AltcoinTrading.NET - How to setup Monero core wallet (for dummies)" layout="responsive" width="700px" height="360px"></amp-img></figure></a></p>

<p>When itâ€™s done itâ€™ll tell you SYNCHRONIZED OK. At this point you can generate the monero CLI wallet, run <code class="highlighter-rouge">./monero-wallet-cli</code>.</p>

<p><a target="_blank" href="https://www.altcointrading.net/img/xmr/monero-cli-3.jpg" title="AltcoinTrading.NET - How to setup Monero core wallet (for dummies)"><figure class="border"><amp-img itemprop="image" src="https://www.altcointrading.net/img/xmr/monero-cli-3.jpg" alt="How to setup Monero core wallet (for dummies)" title="AltcoinTrading.NET - How to setup Monero core wallet (for dummies)" layout="responsive" width="700px" height="360px"></amp-img></figure></a></p>

<p>The client will ask for a name of the wallet and a password. It will generate your address and seed for you so copy the address and write the seed on paper. You should have the monero deamon running.</p>

<p>Now, right now and until you <code class="highlighter-rouge">exit</code> this process you are in the CLI wallet interface. You only need to know the following:</p>

<ul>
  <li>To check your balance, type <code class="highlighter-rouge">refresh</code>.</li>
  <li>To send Monero, type <code class="highlighter-rouge">transfer [address] [amount]</code>.</li>
  <li>To leave the CLI wallet, type <code class="highlighter-rouge">save</code>, wait for response and then type <code class="highlighter-rouge">exit</code>.</li>
</ul>

